+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01TYnrDAY1t4UnHJRktFDxd2","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Good progress — down from 12 failures to 3. There are two remaining issues:\n\n1. **Inventory tests failing**: The `EventBus` uses a module-level global handler registry, so handlers from previous tests persist. The `beforeEach` creates a new `EventBus` but doesn't `clear()` the global handlers. But wait — the tests call `new EventBus()` and the global handlers persist... Let me check more carefully.\n\nThe EventBus is using `globalHandlers` at module level. When the inventory test `beforeEach` creates a new `EventBus`, it doesn't clear the old handlers. But the `orders.test.ts` `beforeEach` also registers handlers via `inventoryService.registerHandlers()` and `billing.registerHandlers()`. Since `globalHandlers` is shared, handlers from the orders test suite could still be registered when the inventory tests run if the bus is never cleared.\n\nWait, but the inventory tests pass in the `orders.test.ts` context because that test sets up its own inventory. The problem is that when the `inventory.test.ts` runs, the global handlers from previous test files may still be registered. Looking more closely at the inventory tests — the tests register handlers via `service.registerHandlers()`, but there may be DUPLICATE handlers from previous test suites if `bus.clear()` isn't called.\n\nActually, looking at the error: `Insufficient stock for product SKU-1` in the inventory tests — this happens when emitting `CREATED` event. The test sets stock to 10 and reserves 3. But if there's a duplicate handler registered (from previous test), it would try to reserve 3 twice — second time failing because only 7 are available.\n\nThe fix should be in the `EventBus` — each `new EventBus()` should have its own handlers, or the `beforeEach` should call `bus.clear()`. Since tests don't call `clear()`, the EventBus needs to use instance-level handlers instead of module-level globals.\n\n2. **Calculator rounding**: The intermediate rounding is causing the issue. Let me trace through:\n   - subtotal = 3*29.99 + 49.99 = 89.97 + 49.99 = 139.96\n   - discount = 139.96 * 0.15 = 20.994, rounded = 20.99\n   - afterDiscount = 139.96 - 20.99 = 118.97, rounded = 118.97\n   - tax = 118.97 * 0.1 = 11.897, rounded = 11.9\n   - total = 118.97 + 11.9 = 130.87\n\nBut the test expects 130.86. The test comment says:\n   - discount = 139.96 * 0.15 = 20.994\n   - after discount = 118.966\n   - tax = 118.966 * 0.1 = 11.8966\n   - total = 130.8626 -> rounded to 130.86\n\nSo the test expects NO intermediate rounding — the discount and tax should be calculated without intermediate rounding, and only the final values should be rounded."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1213,"cache_read_input_tokens":49373,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1213,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b51607b8-49ee-45e0-91aa-5308df462f0a","uuid":"0f9f169e-2433-4b65-928c-35a9f13d553b"}
